\begin_layout Standard
In section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Basis-and-Dimension"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 it was noted that given a basis for a vector space, each vector has a unique
 (exactly one) representation as a linear combination of the vectors in
 the basis.
 That means there is a one-to-one correspondence between elements in the
 vector space and linear combinations of vectors in the basis.
 Each vector in the vector space can be identified by its corresponding
 linear combination, or more succinctly, by the list of coefficients in
 that linear combination.
 These coefficient lists serve as unique identifiers for the vectors much
 the same way social security numbers serve as unique identifiers for people.
 Each vector/person is associated with exactly one string of numbers.
 The difference is each vector actually has a different unique identifiers
 for each basis, somewhat analogous to a person having a different social
 security number for each country on the planet.
 One SSN is useful in France while another is useful in Mali.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As pointed out in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Basis-and-Dimension"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{E}=\{I_{:,1},I_{:,2},\ldots,I_{:,n}\}
\]

\end_inset

is a basis for the vector space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}_{n\times1}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 (the collection of all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times1$
\end_inset

 matrices with real coefficients), better known as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Technically, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}_{n\times1}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 are isomorphic (see section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Isomorphisms"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Writing a vector in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 as a linear combination of these basis elements is a simple matter:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle x_{1},x_{2},\ldots,x_{n}\rangle=x_{1}I_{:,1}+x_{2}I_{:,2}+\cdots+x_{n}I_{:,n},
\]

\end_inset

and this is the only such linear combination.
 If we write the coefficients as a column vector decorated with the name
 of the basis as in 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\begin{array}{c}
x_{1}\\
x_{2}\\
\vdots\\
x_{n}
\end{array}\right]_{\mathcal{E}}$
\end_inset

, we have what is known as a 
\series bold
coordinate vector
\series default
.
 Given a different basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}=\{\mathbf{v}_{1},\mathbf{v}_{2},\ldots,\mathbf{v}_{n}\}$
\end_inset

, writing 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle x_{1},x_{2},\ldots,x_{n}\rangle$
\end_inset

 as a linear combination would require different coefficients:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle x_{1},x_{2},\ldots,x_{n}\rangle=c_{1}\mathbf{v}_{1}+c_{2}\mathbf{v}_{2}+\cdots+c_{n}\mathbf{v}_{n}
\]

\end_inset

and would result in a different coordinate vector, 
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle \left[\begin{array}{c}
c_{1}\\
c_{2}\\
\vdots\\
c_{n}
\end{array}\right]_{\mathcal{B}}}$
\end_inset

, read as the coordinate vector with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It should be noted that the order of the elements in a basis matters, and
 that the entries in the coordinate vector must correspond to this ordering.
 The first entry of the coordinate vector corresponds with the first vector
 in the basis.
 The second entry of the coordinate vector corresponds with the second vector
 in the basis.
 And so on.
 This correspondence is required to maintain the uniqueness of representation.
 Different orderings of the same basis may provide different coordinate
 vectors for certain vectors.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}=\{I_{:,2},I_{:,1},\ldots,I_{:,n}\}$
\end_inset

 is different from the standard basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{E}$
\end_inset

 (even though, as sets, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{E}$
\end_inset

 are equal).
 Of course, it is still true that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle x_{1},x_{2},\ldots,x_{n}\rangle=x_{1}I_{:,1}+x_{2}I_{:,2}+\cdots+x_{n}I_{:,n}.
\]

\end_inset

This is simply how we understand the notations.
 But this means 
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle \left[\begin{array}{c}
x_{2}\\
x_{1}\\
\vdots\\
x_{n}
\end{array}\right]_{\mathcal{B}}}$
\end_inset

 is the coordinate vector of 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle x_{1},x_{2},\ldots,x_{n}\rangle$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\begin{array}{c}
x_{1}\\
x_{2}\\
\vdots\\
x_{n}
\end{array}\right]_{\mathcal{E}}=\left[\begin{array}{c}
x_{2}\\
x_{1}\\
\vdots\\
x_{n}
\end{array}\right]_{\mathcal{B}}.
\]

\end_inset

 Letting 
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle \mathcal{C}=\left\{ \left[\begin{array}{c}
1\\
0\\
0
\end{array}\right]_{\mathcal{E}},\left[\begin{array}{c}
1\\
1\\
0
\end{array}\right]_{\mathcal{E}},\left[\begin{array}{c}
1\\
1\\
1
\end{array}\right]_{\mathcal{E}}\right\} }$
\end_inset

, can you verify that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\begin{array}{c}
6\\
4\\
-3
\end{array}\right]_{\mathcal{E}}=\left[\begin{array}{c}
4\\
6\\
-3
\end{array}\right]_{\mathcal{B}}=\left[\begin{array}{c}
2\\
7\\
-3
\end{array}\right]_{\mathcal{C}}?
\]

\end_inset

Answer on page 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "ans:equivalent-coordinate-vectors"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notice that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\begin{array}{c}
2\\
7\\
-3
\end{array}\right]_{\mathcal{C}}=2\left[\begin{array}{c}
1\\
0\\
0
\end{array}\right]_{\mathcal{E}}+7\left[\begin{array}{c}
1\\
1\\
0
\end{array}\right]_{\mathcal{E}}-3\left[\begin{array}{c}
1\\
1\\
1
\end{array}\right]_{\mathcal{E}}=\left(\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
1 & 1 & 1\\
0 & 1 & 1\\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{c}
2\\
7\\
-3
\end{array}\right]\right)_{\mathcal{E}}
\]

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\begin{array}{c}
4\\
6\\
-3
\end{array}\right]_{\mathcal{B}}=4\left[\begin{array}{c}
0\\
1\\
0
\end{array}\right]_{\mathcal{E}}+6\left[\begin{array}{c}
1\\
0\\
0
\end{array}\right]_{\mathcal{E}}-3\left[\begin{array}{c}
0\\
0\\
1
\end{array}\right]_{\mathcal{E}}=\left(\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
0 & 1 & 0\\
1 & 0 & 0\\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{c}
4\\
6\\
-3
\end{array}\right]\right)_{\mathcal{E}}.
\]

\end_inset

In general, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 is a basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathcal{B}\right]_{\mathcal{E}}$
\end_inset

 is the matrix whose columns are the vectors of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

, respecting order, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left[\mathbf{v}\right]_{\mathcal{E}}=\left[\mathcal{B}\right]_{\mathcal{E}}\left[\mathbf{v}\right]_{\mathcal{B}}\label{eq:to-standard-basis}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathbf{v}\right]_{\mathcal{D}}$
\end_inset

 denotes the coordinate vector of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 with respect to the basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But there is nothing special about the standard basis beyond the fact that
 it is the most familiar.
 If the vectors in basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 are written with respect to the basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathcal{B}\right]_{\mathcal{C}}$
\end_inset

 is the matrix whose columns are these vectors, respecting order, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left[\mathbf{v}\right]_{\mathcal{C}}=\left[\mathcal{B}\right]_{\mathcal{C}}\left[\mathbf{v}\right]_{\mathcal{B}}.\label{eq:change-of-basis}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This can be verified by direct calculation.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}=\{\mathbf{b}_{1},\mathbf{b}_{2},\ldots,\mathbf{b}_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}=\{\mathbf{c}_{1},\mathbf{c}_{2},\ldots,\mathbf{c}_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 and write the vectors of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathbf{b}_{1} & =M_{1,1}\mathbf{c}_{1}+M_{2,1}\mathbf{c}_{2}+\cdots+M_{n,1}\mathbf{c}_{n}\nonumber \\
\mathbf{b}_{2} & =M_{1,2}\mathbf{c}_{1}+M_{2,2}\mathbf{c}_{2}+\cdots+M_{n,2}\mathbf{c}_{n}\nonumber \\
 & \vdots\nonumber \\
\mathbf{b}_{n} & =M_{1,n}\mathbf{c}_{1}+M_{2,n}\mathbf{c}_{2}+\cdots+M_{n,n}\mathbf{c}_{n}\label{eq:B-wrt-C}
\end{align}

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{v}=v_{1}\mathbf{b}_{1}+v_{2}\mathbf{b}_{2}+\cdots+v_{n}\mathbf{b}_{n}.\label{eq:v-wrt-B}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\mathcal{B}\right]_{\mathcal{C}}=\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
M_{1,1} & M_{1,2} & \cdots & M_{1,n}\\
M_{2,1} & M_{2,2} & \cdots & M_{2,n}\\
\vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
M_{n,1} & M_{n,2} & \cdots & M_{n,n}
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left[\mathcal{B}\right]_{\mathcal{C}}\left[\mathbf{v}\right]_{\mathcal{B}} & =v_{1}\left[\begin{array}{c}
M_{1,1}\\
M_{2,1}\\
\vdots\\
M_{n,1}
\end{array}\right]+v_{2}\left[\begin{array}{c}
M_{1,2}\\
M_{2,2}\\
\vdots\\
M_{n,2}
\end{array}\right]+\cdots+v_{n}\left[\begin{array}{c}
M_{1,n}\\
M_{2,n}\\
\vdots\\
M_{n,n}
\end{array}\right]\nonumber \\
 & =\left[\begin{array}{c}
v_{1}M_{1,1}+v_{2}M_{1,2}+\cdots+v_{n}M_{1,n}\\
v_{1}M_{2,1}+v_{2}M_{2,2}+\cdots+v_{n}M_{2,n}\\
\vdots\\
v_{1}M_{n,1}+v_{2}M_{n,2}+\cdots+v_{n}M_{n,n}
\end{array}\right].\label{eq:v-wrt-C}
\end{align}

\end_inset

On the other hand, direct substitution of (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:B-wrt-C"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) into (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:v-wrt-B"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) yields
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{v} & =v_{1}\left(M_{1,1}\mathbf{c}_{1}+M_{2,1}\mathbf{c}_{2}+\cdots+M_{n,1}\mathbf{c}_{n}\right)\\
 & \phantom{=}\quad+v_{2}\left(M_{1,2}\mathbf{c}_{1}+M_{2,2}\mathbf{c}_{2}+\cdots+M_{n,2}\mathbf{c}_{n}\right)\\
 & \phantom{=}\qquad\vdots\\
 & \phantom{=}\quad+v_{n}\left(M_{1,n}\mathbf{c}_{1}+M_{2,n}\mathbf{c}_{2}+\cdots+M_{n,n}\mathbf{c}_{n}\right)\\
 & =\left(v_{1}M_{1,1}+v_{2}M_{1,2}+\cdots+v_{n}M_{1,n}\right)\mathbf{c}_{1}\\
 & \phantom{=}\quad+\left(v_{1}M_{2,1}+v_{2}M_{2,2}+\cdots+v_{n}M_{2,n}\right)\mathbf{c}_{2}\\
 & \phantom{=}\qquad\vdots\\
 & \phantom{=}\quad+\left(v_{1}M_{n,1}+v_{2}M_{n,2}+\cdots+v_{n}M_{n,n}\right)\mathbf{c}_{n}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which verifies that (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:v-wrt-C"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathbf{v}\right]_{\mathcal{C}}$
\end_inset

.
 Equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:change-of-basis"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) is one formula for a so-called 
\series bold
change of basis
\series default
.
 It gives a formula for changing the basis with respect to which 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is written from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Being a basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 contains 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 linearly independent vectors with 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 entries each, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathcal{B}\right]_{\mathcal{C}}$
\end_inset

 is invertible for any basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 written with respect to any basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

 (how it is written is actually immaterial as far as linear independence
 is concerned).
 In particular, if both bases 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

 are written with respect to the standard basis and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is an arbitrary vector, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathbf{v}\right]_{\mathcal{E}}=\left[\mathcal{B}\right]_{\mathcal{E}}\left[\mathbf{v}\right]_{\mathcal{B}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathbf{v}\right]_{\mathcal{E}}=\left[\mathcal{C}\right]_{\mathcal{E}}\left[\mathbf{v}\right]_{\mathcal{C}}$
\end_inset

, so
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\mathcal{B}\right]_{\mathcal{E}}\left[\mathbf{v}\right]_{\mathcal{B}}=\left[\mathcal{C}\right]_{\mathcal{E}}\left[\mathbf{v}\right]_{\mathcal{C}}
\]

\end_inset

and we can conclude
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\mathcal{C}\right]_{\mathcal{E}}^{-1}\left[\mathcal{B}\right]_{\mathcal{E}}\left[\mathbf{v}\right]_{\mathcal{B}}=\left[\mathbf{v}\right]_{\mathcal{C}}\quad\text{and}\quad\left[\mathbf{v}\right]_{\mathcal{B}}=\left[\mathcal{B}\right]_{\mathcal{E}}^{-1}\left[\mathcal{C}\right]_{\mathcal{E}}\left[\mathbf{v}\right]_{\mathcal{C}}.
\]

\end_inset

Comparing this to (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:change-of-basis"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) it must be that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathcal{C}\right]_{\mathcal{E}}^{-1}\left[\mathcal{B}\right]_{\mathcal{E}}=\left[\mathcal{B}\right]_{\mathcal{C}}$
\end_inset

 or
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left[\mathbf{v}\right]_{\mathcal{C}}=\left[\mathcal{C}\right]_{\mathcal{E}}^{-1}\left[\mathcal{B}\right]_{\mathcal{E}}\left[\mathbf{v}\right]_{\mathcal{B}}.\label{eq:change-of-basis-2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In retrospect, this should not be surprising.
 Multiplying 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathbf{v}\right]_{\mathcal{B}}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathcal{B}\right]_{\mathcal{E}}$
\end_inset

 gives 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathbf{v}\right]_{\mathcal{E}}$
\end_inset

 (see equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:to-standard-basis"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

)).
 This same equation tells us that multiplying 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathbf{v}\right]_{\mathcal{E}}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathcal{C}\right]_{\mathcal{E}}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 gives 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathbf{v}\right]_{\mathcal{C}}$
\end_inset

.
 Diagrammatically
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\mathbf{v}\right]_{\mathcal{B}}\overset{\text{times }\left[\mathcal{B}\right]_{\mathcal{E}}}{\longrightarrow}\left[\mathbf{v}\right]_{\mathcal{E}}\overset{\text{times }\left[\mathcal{C}\right]_{\mathcal{E}}^{-1}}{\longrightarrow}\left[\mathbf{v}\right]_{\mathcal{C}},
\]

\end_inset

which is just another way to write (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:change-of-basis-2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

